03 05:02:11','2018-02-03 05:02:11','','Diversity_SMM','','inherit','open','closed','','diversity_smm','','','2018-02-03 05:02:11','2018-02-03 05:02:11','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Diversity_SMM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(43,1,'2018-02-03 05:02:15','2018-02-03 05:02:15','','Search-Doc-Icon-1','','inherit','open','closed','','search-doc-icon-1','','','2018-02-03 05:02:15','2018-02-03 05:02:15','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Search-Doc-Icon-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(44,1,'2018-02-03 05:06:56','2018-02-03 05:06:56','','download','','inherit','open','closed','','download','','','2018-02-03 05:06:56','2018-02-03 05:06:56','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/download.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(45,1,'2018-02-03 05:15:35','2018-02-03 05:15:35','','imageedit_2_9553048342','','inherit','open','closed','','imageedit_2_9553048342','','','2018-02-03 07:01:44','2018-02-03 07:01:44','',53,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/imageedit_2_9553048342.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(53,1,'2018-02-03 06:59:57','2018-02-03 06:59:57','<img src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/imageedit_2_9553048342-300x212.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"238\" height=\"168\" class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-45\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Medical statistics</b> deals with applications of<b>statistics</b> to <b>medicine</b> and the health sciences, including epidemiology, public health, forensic<b>medicine</b>, and clinical research. ... However, \"biostatistics\" more commonly connotes all applications of <b>statistics</b> to biology. <b>Medical Statistics</b> are a sub discipline of <b>Statistics</b>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p class=\"f-body f-body--w-dropcap\">to increase colorectal cancer screening rates, ABC Health System decides to send birthday cards to patients when they turn 50. The cards read, “It’s your 50th birthday — treat yourself to a colonoscopy!” and contain coupons for free Gatorade and MiraLAX and a book of crossword puzzles to keep the recipient occupied while on the toilet. ABC’s idea is that some whimsy might help overcome colonoscopy’s “ickiness” barrier. XYZ Health System has the same goal. The birthday cards they send include notification of a prescheduled colonoscopy appointment, with options for selecting a more convenient time. Their idea is to frame screening as the default. Both ABC and XYZ health systems plan evaluations with pre–post designs to assess whether screening rates change. No one objects, since the approaches are well-meaning, plausible, safe, and consistent with clinical guidelines.</p>\r\n<p class=\"f-body\">QRS Health System arrives at the same two ideas, but proposes to randomly assign patients to either the whimsical card, the prescheduled-appointment card, or usual messaging. Scientifically, their approach is better than what ABC and XYZ plan individually or combined, since they evaluate these two ideas concurrently, by random allocation, and against a control of usual care — addressing concerns about pre–post designs and secular trends. Everyone wins, except now that they are randomly assigning patients to interventions, it seems obvious they are doing research, and maybe their design needs to be evaluated by the institutional review board (IRB).</p>\r\n<p class=\"f-body\">The portion of the Code of Federal Regulations often called “the Common Rule” (§46.116) specifies that informed consent can be waived when: “(1) The research involves no more than minimal risk to the subjects; (2) The waiver or alteration will not adversely affect the rights and welfare of the subjects; [and] (3) The research could not practicably be carried out without the waiver or alteration.” The QRS IRB, seeing that patients will be contacted by birthday card anyway, concludes that asking their permission is practicable and, seeing randomization, they conclude that not asking for permission violates patients’ rights not to participate. They insist that QRS patients explicitly consent to the evaluation. Now, two interventions that were deemed acceptable for the total population without obtaining consent become subject to additional standards when applied by random allocation — even though randomization produces more useful information without increasing risk.</p>\r\n<p class=\"f-body\">Many QRS patients, facing bothersome consent procedures or wary of experiments, decline. QRS is left with a sample that no longer represents the underlying population. Maybe it differs demographically or contains a higher proportion of more motivated patients — those willing to complete the consent procedures and so perhaps also more motivated to complete cancer screening, a group that may exclude the patients who could benefit the most. The trial no longer reflects what might happen should QRS roll out either policy to everyone. What went wrong?</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Statistics','','trash','closed','closed','','statistics__trashed','','','2018-03-18 23:29:40','2018-03-18 17:59:40','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=53',2,'page','',0),(54,1,'2018-02-03 06:56:46','2018-02-03 06:56:46','<div class=\"col-md-5\"><h3>About Statistics Generater</h3>Need more details? Please check our full documentation for detailed information on how to use statistics generator .<br />.</div><div class=\"col-md-6 col-md-offset-1\"></div><div><img src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/download.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"225\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-44\" /></div>','HOME','','publish','closed','closed','','hestia-front','','','2018-03-21 04:58:10','2018-03-20 23:28:10','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/hestia-front/',0,'page','',0),(55,1,'2018-02-03 06:59:57','2018-02-03 06:59:57','','Statistics','','inherit','closed','closed','','53-revision-v1','','','2018-02-03 06:59:57','2018-02-03 06:59:57','',53,'http://localhost/wordpress/2018/0